# =============================================================================
# .gitattributes — Line ending normalisation
#
# This file tells Git how to handle line endings when files are checked out
# on different operating systems. Without it, a Windows contributor's Git
# client (configured with core.autocrlf=true) will convert Unix line endings
# (LF, \n) to Windows line endings (CRLF, \r\n) in shell scripts. Shell
# scripts with CRLF line endings fail inside Linux containers with the
# cryptic error: "bash: \r: command not found".
#
# The rules below solve this without requiring every contributor to change
# their Git configuration:
#
#   * = text=auto         → Git normalises all text files to LF in the repo.
#                           On checkout, Windows gets CRLF for text files
#                           (which is fine for .py, .md, .txt etc.) and
#                           Linux/macOS get LF.
#
#   *.sh eol=lf           → Shell scripts ALWAYS get LF on checkout,
#                           regardless of the contributor's OS or Git config.
#
#   *.sh text eol=lf      → Belt-and-suspenders: also marks .sh as text
#                           (not binary) so Git diffs show changes.
# =============================================================================

# Default: normalise all text files
* text=auto

# Shell scripts must always use Unix line endings
*.sh text eol=lf

# Docker-related files are used in Linux containers — keep LF
Dockerfile text eol=lf
docker-compose.yml text eol=lf
entrypoint.sh text eol=lf

# Python files — LF everywhere for consistency
*.py text eol=lf

# Markdown and config — let the OS normalise these (safe either way)
*.md text
*.txt text
*.env text
*.example text
requirements.txt text
